			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2023</a> paper:</span><br><i>A Tool for the Definition and Deployment of Platform-Independent Bots on Open Source Projects</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/AdemAit.html">Adem Ait</a>, <a href="../profile/JavierLuisCánovasIzquierdo.html">Javier Luis Cánovas Izquierdo</a>, <a href="../profile/JordiCabot.html">Jordi Cabot</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/3623476.3623524">10.1145/3623476.3623524</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t2d.html"><span class="tagM">T2D: Deployment</span></a><ul><li> The paper focuses on defining and deploying bots in a platform-independent way across open-source projects.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL">T4A: Workbenches</span></a><ul><li> The contribution is realized as a toolchain for specifying bots and deploying them to target repositories.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagL">T3C: DSLs</span></a><ul><li> The bot definitions resemble a domain-specific specification language for project automation tasks.
</li></ul></li></ul>
